{{Taxobox| name = Northern cavefish| image = Amblyopsis spelaeus.jpg| image_width = 300px| status = VU | status_system = IUCN2.3| regnum = Animalia| phylum = Chordata| classis = Actinopterygii| ordo = Percopsiformes| familia = Amblyopsidae| genus = Amblyopsis| species = A. spelea| binomial = Amblyopsis spelea| binomial_authority = (DeKay, 1842)}}

The northern cavefish or northern blindfish, Amblyopsis spelea, is found in caves through Kentucky and southern Indiana. It is listed as a threatened species in the United States and the IUCN lists the species as vulnerable.

The White River, flowing east to west south of Bedford, Indiana, delimits the northern range of Amblyopsis spelea. These fish are not found in caves north of the White River. 

